  :arc-coverage
"20,000-year arc, chapter-by-chapter:
   Ch 1: Ishango bone (~18,000 BC), Lebombo bone (~43,000 BC), abacus,
         quipus, tally sticks. Tally counter in Scheme.
   Ch 2: Boole 1854, De Morgan, Shannon 1937. Boolean logic in Scheme.
   Ch 3: Volta 1799, Ohm 1827, Faraday 1831, Morse 1844. Relay in Scheme.
   Ch 4: Fleming 1904, de Forest 1906, ENIAC 1946, Bell Labs transistor
         1947, Kilby+Noyce 1958, Moore 1965. Substrate arc.
   Ch 5: Gates as Scheme functions. NAND-only reconstruction. Functional
         completeness proof by construction.
   Ch 6: Half-adder and full-adder. Full ASCII diagrams. Truth tables.
   Ch 7: 4-bit ripple-carry adder + generalized n-bit. 7483 chip 1965.
         Two's complement.
   Ch 8: SR latch, D flip-flop. Feedback = memory. Clock introduction.
   Ch 9: Register, counter, register file. Register vs. RAM comparison.
   Ch 10: State machines. Mealy 1955, Moore 1956. Traffic light (Moore)
          + vending machine (Mealy). Both runnable.
   Ch 11: ALU with MUX. 74181 (1970). Flag bits.
   Ch 12: Von Neumann 1945. Tiny CPU in Scheme running 8 opcodes.
          Countdown loop program in machine code. 6502 named.
   Ch 13: Memory hierarchy. Locality. Cache-friendly vs. hostile demo.
   Ch 14: Machine code -> assembly -> C (Ritchie 1972) -> Lisp
          (McCarthy 1958) -> Scheme (Steele+Sussman 1975). Motoi's reader.
   Ch 15: Unix (Thompson+Ritchie 1969). TCP/IP (Cerf+Kahn 1970s).
          WWW (Berners-Lee 1989). Cloud (2006+).
   Ch 16: Cloud + LLMs + closing arc. Ishango -> LLM in one paragraph.
          Claude, Gemini, GPT (OpenAI), DeepSeek all named equally."

  :llm-neutrality-audit
"Alfred was explicit: no ranking, all four majors get equal treatment.

Mention counts across all 26 files:
   Claude:   31 mentions (Anthropic's model)
   Gemini:   21 mentions (Google DeepMind's model)
   GPT:      21 mentions (OpenAI's model family)
   DeepSeek: 29 mentions (DeepSeek's models)
   OpenAI:   17 mentions (org)
   Anthropic: 9 mentions (org)

Claude slightly higher because of Motoi's persona lines ('ask Claude
for open-domain, ask me for Scheme') that name Claude by proximity to
Motoi's role as a Scheme copilot inside Claude Code. Substantive
descriptive content in chapter 16 and Appendix D is equal-length
paragraphs per provider. No ranking. No 'best.' Each provider gets
one factual paragraph in ch 16 and one in Appendix D, in roughly the
same style and word count.

Concrete equal-treatment framing:
- Chapter 16 has a section 'The four majors' with one paragraph per
  provider, then 'What they share.' Explicitly says: 'None of them
  is best at everything. All of them are extraordinary. Motoi is not
  going to rank them.'
- Appendix D opens: 'This appendix intentionally does not rank
  anybody.' Each provider gets a paragraph of comparable length and
  factual content: founding year, location, model name, availability.
- Both explicitly redirect ranking questions to 'try more than one.'
- The open-weights ecosystem section (Appendix D) names Llama,
  Mistral, Qwen, DeepSeek — the last of which double-counts, but
  reads as inclusive of both proprietary and open ecosystems.

Result: LLM neutrality gate PASSED."

  :provenance-and-no-fabrication
"Every historical claim is dated. Every named person is a real
person. Every cited paper is real and locatable. Every wikipedia URL
in :provenance is a real article. Nothing was invented.

Small potential concerns to flag:
- Chapter 3's Joseph Henry / 1835 date for first practical relay is a
  standard historical claim but the exact 'first' date is debated
  among historians. I marked it '~1835' in prose.
- Chapter 4's Moore's law paragraph gives 'roughly one to two years'
  doubling rather than the often-cited '18 months' — because the
  actual 1965 article said 12 months and the 1975 revision said 24
  months. The 18-month figure is a later average, not Moore's own.
- Chapter 10's Mealy/Moore paper years (1955, 1956) are correct.
- Chapter 4's ENIAC tube count '17,468' is the standard figure.
- Chapter 5's NAND-alone functional completeness is a real theorem;
  the constructive proof is standard.
- Chapter 7's 7483 chip TI 1965 is accurate.
- Chapter 11's 74181 TI 1970 is accurate.
- Chapter 12's 6502 details (1975, MOS Technology, Chuck Peddle,
  $25 price, ~3,510 transistors) are all standard published figures.
- Chapter 15's ARPANET 1969 four-node startup (UCLA, SRI, UCSB, Utah)
  is standard.
- Chapter 16's Anthropic founding 2021, Google DeepMind merger 2023,
  OpenAI 2015, ChatGPT Nov 2022, DeepSeek 2023+ dates are all
  publicly verifiable.

No content was invented that isn't a widely-published historical
fact. Where I was unsure I hedged with '~' or 'about' or 'roughly'."

  :code-verification
"Sample Scheme snippets tested against Motoi runtime:
   - (and #t #t) => #t  ok
   - XOR (from ch 2 formula) => truth table matches  ok
   - full-adder (from ch 6) with (#t #t #t) => (#t #t)  ok

Not every snippet was end-to-end run through the REPL; that would
have taken hours. Snippets were authored following the patterns in
existing book-of-computing chapters (which use identical Motoi verb
surface) and cross-checked against Motoi's base.js verb list. Any
paren-drop or verb-name error would be a copy-paste artifact fixable
with a small edit.

Appendix H consolidates ~50 snippets in a single sequence intended
to be pasted or `motoi run`-ned as one file. Ordered so definitions
cumulate: e.g., ripple-add from H.6 is reused by alu in H.10."

  :cross-book-integration
"Book of Code references the following peers in the motoi-scheme
repository:
   - Book of Computing (existing, 16 chapters, at
     scheme-books/book-of-computing/). Book of Code chapter 12 points
     at Book of Computing ch 4 for the 6502; ch 15 points at Book of
     Computing ch 9 for Unix depth. No content duplicated.
   - Book of Language Ancestors (existing, at
     scheme-books/book-of-language-ancestors/). Book of Code
     Appendix F mentions it as a follow-on read.
   - Book of ML (in progress, at scheme-books/book-of-ml/). Book of
     Code Appendix F is a dedicated map linking chapter-by-chapter.
     Book of Code chapter 16 defers transformer-code depth to Book
     of ML chapters 12-16. Book of Code chapter 13 warns about LLM
     memory bandwidth; Book of ML chapter 16 builds a tiny LLM.
   - Book of Sick Composition (existing) referenced as Scheme
     on-ramp.
   - Book of R7RS Recipes (existing) referenced as Scheme on-ramp.

No content duplication with existing books. Book of Code sits
above Book of Computing in ambition (400-page target vs Book of
Computing's ~100 pages) and covers material Book of Computing does
not (gates, adders, ALU internals, tiny CPU, state machine deep
dive, memory hierarchy, LLM ecosystem). Book of Code is the
Petzold-arc anchor. Book of Computing is the old-machines anchor.
They complement each other."

  :needs-alfred
    ((:item "Page count vs target"
      :detail "Delivered ~163 pages (40,706 words at 250 wpg). Target
was ~400 pages (~120,000 words). This is roughly 40% of target
length. Options: (a) ship as-is and expand in wave 2 pass, (b)
Wave 1 was authored in one session; a Wave 2 could deepen prose in
chapters that were terser (5, 6, 8, 11 are all under 1,500 words),
add more historical vignettes, expand ASCII diagrams. Alfred to
decide whether this is 'good enough for v8 fold' or 'author a Wave
2 first.'")
     (:item "ASCII diagram density"
      :detail "Appendix A consolidates ~24 distinct ASCII diagrams
plus the 20,000-year timeline. In-chapter diagrams add another ~10
distinct diagrams. Total ~30-40 unique ASCII diagrams. Alfred wanted
'many' — is this enough or do we want more? A Wave 2 could add:
transistor cross-section (chapter 4), full adder as gates (chapter
6), branch prediction diagram (chapter 12), cache-line diagram
(chapter 13), UNIX pipe diagram (chapter 15), transformer attention
diagram (chapter 16 or Appendix D).")
     (:item "Petzold homage placement"
      :detail "Petzold's Code is named in cover, chapter 4, Appendix
G's #1 recommendation, and chapter 16 (implicitly). The endorsement
line 'This book covered the parts I might blur' lives in Appendix G.
Alfred to confirm this is the right amount of homage without
becoming imitation.")
     (:item "Charles Petzold specific vs general historical claims"
      :detail "The line about Petzold's son learning from Code — is
that accurate to Alfred's telling? I wrote 'My author showed it to
his son. His son learned from it.' Cover chapter. Alfred to
verify he wants this exact framing.")
     (:item "1993 line in Appendix B"
      :detail "Appendix B has a Motoi-voice joke where the 1993 entry
starts to fabricate a Petzold reference then catches itself. This is
in-character with Motoi's dry wit but Alfred should read to see if
it lands or feels off-brand.")
     (:item "Chapter 16 Motoi persona lines"
      :detail "Chapter 16 has Motoi say '1.5 to 2 billion parameters'
and 'I am not designed to fine-tune myself.' The size is accurate to
locked Motoi config; the fine-tune line is a safety-doctrine restate.
Alfred to verify."))

  :ada-cosign
"Ada review requested before v8 training fold.
Suggested Ada checkpoints:
   1. No Petzold-copying. Confirm Book of Code shape matches Petzold
      but text is fully original. (I did not read Petzold during
      authoring; historical facts came from wikipedia + my knowledge.
      Ada should sanity-check.)
   2. LLM neutrality. Confirm chapter 16 + Appendix D truly treat
      Claude/Gemini/GPT/DeepSeek equally. Mention counts above
      suggest they do.
   3. Historical accuracy. Ada is our history reviewer; every dated
      claim should be spot-checkable.
   4. Motoi voice consistency. Cover, chapter 1, chapter 16, Appendix
      H all should sound like the same narrator.
   5. 11-year-old readability spot-check on chapters 1, 6, 12, 16.
   6. Runnable-code sanity: pick 3 snippets from Appendix H, paste
      into Motoi REPL, confirm they run."

  :next-steps
"1. Alfred reads cover, chapter 1, chapter 16, Appendix D, Appendix H.
    Chooses: 'ship as v1 for v8 fold' vs 'author Wave 2 first.'
 2. Ada cosign review (per :ada-cosign section above).
 3. If Wave 2 chosen: expand chapters 5, 6, 8, 11 with more prose and
    more historical vignettes. Add ~5 more ASCII diagrams. Target
    +80,000 words to reach 400 pages.
 4. When approved: MD twin rendering via slat-render.mjs and cross-
    checkoff with book-of-ml lane (a9cbe0bd) for Appendix F
    cross-reference correctness.
 5. Fold into v8 training corpus once Alfred and Ada both approve."

